Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
get_oa_default_rule_lib(25.10)                  get_oa_default_rule_lib(25.10)

Name
       get_oa_default_rule_lib  - Searches through a specified library (or li-
       braries) to check whether a specified LDRS exists or not

Syntax
       get_oa_default_rule_lib

       [-help]

       [-rule <rule_name>]

       [-libs <lib_list>]

       [-verbose]

       Searches through a specified library (or libraries) to check whether  a
       specified  LDRS  exists or not. You can run this check before reading a
       library.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes type and default infor-
              mation for each get_oa_default_rule_lib parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man get_oa_default_rule_lib

       -libs <lib_list>
              Specifies the list of library names to search  through.  If  not
              specified, all libraries are searched.

       -rule <rule_name>
              Specifies the name of the rule to find.

              If  not specified, the init_oa_default_rule variable is used. If
              the variable has an empty  string  value,  the  standard  lookup
              (LEFDefaultRouteSpec by type, then by name) is used.

              If  the  specified  <rule_name> does not exist, the command dis-
              plays an error such as:

              Rule '<rule_name>' was not found in specified libraries.

              If the specified <rule_name> is found, the command  returns  the
              name  of  the library where the specified <rule_name> was found.
              This could be from the -libs <lib_list> or any ITDB that one  of
              those libraries refers to.

              If  the  specified  <rule_name> is found but is not a legal LDRS
              type as determined by the OAX reader code, the command  displays
              an error such as:

              Constraint    group   '<rule_name>'   was   found   in   library
              '<lib_name>', but is not a legal LEFDefaultRouteSpec

       -verbose
              Echoes details of library name where the rule was found (includ-
              ing descending  through  technology  references  from  libraries
              specified in the <lib_list>.

Examples
              *

                The following example shows how get_oa_default_rule_lib can be
                used  to  search for a specific library and the graph of techs
                that it references:

                set init_oa_ref_lib "tech_lib macro_lib"

                set init_oa_default_rule LDRS_65nm_6lm

                set tech_lib [lindex $init_oa_ref_lib 0]

                set lib_found [get_oa_default_rule_lib -libs $tech_lib] #  use
                the init_oa_default_rule to look up the library

                if {$lib_found != ""} {

                 Puts "$init_oa_default_rule was found in $lib_found or in the
                graph of libraries that $tech_lib references"

                } else {

                 Puts "$init_oa_default_rule was not found in $tech_lib nor in
                the graph of libraries that $tech_lib references"

                }

              * The  following  command  shows  how the -verbose option can be
                used:

                get_oa_default_rule_lib -verbose

                INFO: Default rule 'LEFDefaultRouteSpec' was found in  library
                'FEOAreflib8'.

                FEOAreflib8

